  "text": "Medical management of Crohn's disease is a fast evolving area, with more medical treatments that have proved their effectiveness in inducing and maintaining the remission. Therefore many studies have attempted to establish whether these therapies can be effective in preventing postoperative recurrence. The results are not very consistent and many therapies have shown little benefit. Mesalamine, nitroimidazole antibiotics, thiopurine analogues (azathioprine and 6-mercaptopurine) have been reported to be effective treatments but have shown limited efficacy in reducing postoperative recurrence [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] .",
